SIMPLE: spire
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spire
<hw>Spire</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>spirare</ets> to breathe. See <er>Spirit</er>.]</ety> <def>To
breathe.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shenstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spire
<hw>Spire</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>spire</ets>,
<ets>spir</ets>, a blade of grass, a young shoot, AS.
<ets>sp⟦imac⟧r</ets>; akin to G. <ets>spier</ets> a blade of grass, Dan.
<ets>spire</ets> a sprout, sprig, Sw. <ets>spira</ets> a spar, Icel.
<ets>sp⟦imac⟧ra</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A slender stalk or blade
in vegetation; <as>as, a <ex>spire</ex> grass or of
wheat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An oak cometh up a little <qex>spire</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A tapering body that shoots up or out to a point in
a conical or pyramidal form. Specifically <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, the roof
of a tower when of a pyramidal form and high in proportion to its width;
also, the pyramidal or aspiring termination of a tower which can not be
said to have a roof, such as that of Strasburg cathedral; the tapering
part of a steeple, or the steeple itself.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With glistering
<xex>spires</xex> and pinnacles adorned.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>spire</qex> of land that stand apart,⟦br⟧
Cleft from the main.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tall <qex>spire</qex> from which the sound of cheerful bells⟦br⟧
Just undulates upon the listening ear.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A tube or fuse for communicating
fire to the chargen in blasting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The top, or uppermost point, of anything; the
summit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>spire</qex> and top of praises.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spire
<hw>Spire</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spired</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spiring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To shoot forth, or up in, or as
if in, a spire.</def> <rj><au>Emerson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is not so apt to <qex>spire</qex> up as the other sorts, being
more inclined to branch into arms.</q> <rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Spire
<hw>Spire</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>spira</ets> coil, twist;
akin to Gr. <?/<?/<?/: cf. F. <ets>spire</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A spiral; a curl; a whorl; a twist.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>The part of a spiral generated in
one revolution of the straight line about the pole. See <er>Spiral</er>,
<pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spire bearer</b></col>. <fld>(Paleon.)</fld> <cd>Same as
<er>Spirifer</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spired</ent>⟦br⟧
